<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Even if world nations meet their environmental commitments, a staggering 53 million tonnes of plastic will enter the world's waters annually by 2030, experts said.</p>

<p>According to the Canadian team, this prediction — based on models of different mitigation strategies — is seven times the amount deemed shocking in 2005.</p>

<p>The researchers added that the world must act now to support a focus on recycling — rather than creating more plastic that will pollute the Earth's rivers and oceans.</p>

<p>Even if world nations meet their environmental commitments, a staggering 53 million tonnes of plastic waste, pictured, will enter the world's waters annually by 2030, experts said</p>

<p>'Unless growth in plastic production and use is halted, a fundamental transformation of the plastic economy to a framework based on recycling is essential,' said paper author and ecologist Chelsea Rochman of the University of Toronto.</p>

<p>End-of-life plastic products need to become valued, rather than waste, she added.</p>

<p>'Worldwide annual emissions to rivers, lakes and oceans could be as much as 53 million metric tonnes by the year 2030,' added paper author and conservation biologist Stephanie Borrelle, also of the University of Toronto.</p>

<p>'That's far beyond the eight million metric tonnes amount that was declared unacceptable in 2015,' she added.</p>

<p>This will occur, she said, 'even if governments around the world meet their ambitious global commitments, and other countries join those efforts to curb plastic pollution.'</p>

<p>In their study, the researchers examined the 24–34 million metric tonnes of plastic emissions that enter oceans, rivers and lakes annually — and modelled future scenarios based on current mitigation strategies.</p>

<p>They determined that we must reduce plastic usage by 25–40 per cent, increase the level of waste management to at least 60 per cent across all economies and recover 40 per cent of annual plastic emissions through cleanup efforts.</p>

<p>'To put that last number into people power, the cleanup alone would require at least one billion people participating in Ocean Conservancy's annual International Coastal Cleanup,' Dr Borrelle explained.</p>

<p>'This would be a Herculean task given this is 660 times the effort of the 2019 cleanup.'</p>

<p>According to the Canadian team, their dire prediction — based on models of different mitigation strategies, as pictured — is seven times the amount deemed shocking in 2005</p>

<p>The researchers added that the world must act now to support a focus on recycling — rather than creating more plastic that will pollute the Earth's rivers and oceans, as pictured</p>

<p>'The global community must coordinate a fundamental transformation of the plastics economy,' said Professor Rochman.</p>

<p>This, she added, must 'reduce the amount of virgin plastic production and re-imagine how we make use and dispose of plastic materials.'</p>

<p>The full findings of the study were published in the journal Science.</p>

